1Ô∏è‚É£ Lambda

AWS Lambda is a serverless compute service.
It lets you run code without provisioning or managing servers.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Event-Driven

Lambda runs code only when an event occurs.
Events can come from S3, API Gateway, DynamoDB, or CloudWatch.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Supported Languages

Lambda supports languages like Python, Node.js, Java, Go, and .NET.
You can choose the language based on your application.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Automatic Scaling

Lambda automatically scales based on the number of incoming requests.
No manual scaling is required.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Pricing

You pay only for execution time and number of requests.
There is no charge when the code is not running.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Execution Environment

Lambda runs code in a short-lived execution environment.
It has limited memory, storage, and execution time.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Security

Lambda uses IAM roles to control permissions.
It can run inside a VPC for network isolation.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Monitoring

Lambda integrates with CloudWatch for logs and metrics.
You can monitor errors, duration, and invocations.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Integration

Lambda integrates with many AWS services like S3, API Gateway, SNS, and DynamoDB.
It is commonly used in serverless architectures.

üîü Use Cases

Lambda is used for file processing, APIs, automation, and real-time data processing.
It is ideal for short-running tasks
